notes: The outbreak began in August 2007 and was caused by a new species, Bundibugyo ebolavirus.

notes: WHO declared an outbreak on March 23rd, 2014; however, the initial case was reported in December 2013. Morbidity includes 1,046 cases (992 confirmed, 798 fatal) during 2015 and 10 cases (8 fatal) from March to April 2016. These figures also include 196 healthcare workers (100 fatal). Cessation of transmission was declared on December 29th, 2015; however, 10 subsequent cases (8 fatal) were reported in March 2016. The outbreak was declared over by WHO on June 10th, 2016. In Guinea, provinces with the highest incidence were Conakry and Macenta, followed by Coyah, Dubréka, Forécariah, Guéckédou, Kérouané, Nzérékoré, Beyla, Boffa, Boké, Faranah, Kankan, Kindia, Lola, Siguiri, Télimélé, Dabola, Dalaba, Fria, Kouroussa, Pita, Yomou, Mali, and Tougué. The overall reported case-fatality rate was 66.7%. Some researchers suspect that the West African outbreak of 2014 began with the exposure of children to a colony of insectivorous free-tailed bats (Mops condylurus) living in a tree in Meliandou, Guinea.
